# MongoDB Standards

## Naming

- **Collections:** plural, `snake_case` or `camelCase` per project (`users`, `orderItems`).
- **Fields:** `camelCase` (JS/TS) or `snake_case` (Python) consistently.
- **IDs:** `_id` (ObjectId or UUID string). Do not expose raw `_id` in public APIs; use a separate `id` field or stringify safely.
- **Dates:** Store in UTC. Use `Date` objects or ISO 8601 strings consistently.

## Schema design

- **Embed** when: one-to-few, data always read together, no independent lifecycle (e.g. order line items).
- **Reference** when: one-to-many, many-to-many, shared across documents (e.g. user reference in orders).
- Avoid unbounded arrays; use pagination or separate collection for large arrays.
- Avoid deep nesting (>3 levels); flatten when queries need to target nested fields.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD - embed line items in order
{
  _id: ObjectId("..."),
  userId: ObjectId("..."),
  items: [
    { productId: ObjectId("..."), quantity: 2, price: 9.99 }
  ],
  total: 19.98
}

// Reference user; embed items (always read with order)
```

## Indexes

- Index **all** fields used in queries, sorts, and aggregations.
- Compound indexes: equality before range; order by fields last.
- Unique indexes for business uniqueness (e.g. `email`).
- Partial indexes for conditional uniqueness: `{ email: 1 }, { unique: true, partialFilterExpression: { deletedAt: null } }`.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
db.users.createIndex({ email: 1 }, { unique: true });
db.orders.createIndex({ userId: 1, createdAt: -1 });
db.products.createIndex({ "category.slug": 1, price: 1 });
```

## Queries

- Use **projection** to return only needed fields. Avoid returning large arrays unless required.
- Use aggregation for complex queries; pipeline stages in logical order.
- Avoid `$where` and JavaScript in queries; use native operators for performance.
- Pagination: `skip`/`limit` for small offsets; cursor-based (`_id` or sort key) for large datasets.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
db.users.find({ status: "active" }, { email: 1, name: 1 }).limit(20);

// ❌ BAD
db.users.find({ status: "active" });  // Returns all fields
```

## Mongoose / ODM

- Define **schemas** with validation. Use required, min/max, enums.
- Validate before write; use middleware for timestamps and hashing.
- Never trust client input; sanitize and validate in application layer.
- Use lean queries when Mongoose documents are not needed: `.lean()`.

## Connection and ops

- **Connection pooling**: Use default pool; tune `maxPoolSize` for load. Close connection on app shutdown.
- **Read preference**: `primary` for writes; `secondaryPreferred` for read-heavy workloads when using replica set.
- **Config from env**: `MONGODB_URI`; never hardcode. Validate at startup; fail fast if unreachable.

## Patterns

- **Soft delete**: Add `deletedAt`; filter with `{ deletedAt: null }`. Use partial index for performance.
- **Change streams**: For real-time sync; requires replica set. Use with resume tokens for reliability.

## Security and monitoring

- **No PII in logs**: Never log `_id`, emails, or sensitive fields. Log counts and IDs only when needed.
- **Backup**: Use `mongodump`/`mongorestore` or managed backups.
- **README**: Document connection string format, restore procedure, and any replica-set topology.

## Checklist

- [ ] Indexes on all query/sort/aggregation fields; compound indexes in correct order.
- [ ] TTL or pagination for unbounded arrays; avoid deep nesting.
- [ ] No `$where` or JS in queries; use projection; `.lean()` when possible.
- [ ] Connection from env; pool tuned; close on shutdown.
- [ ] No PII in logs; soft delete with partial index when needed.
